00:28:49,080 --> 00:28:52,200
in what is shaping up to be
a long and acrimonious bid

478
00:28:52,240 --> 00:28:54,000
against popular incumbent
Edmund G. Brown. 

479
00:28:54,040 --> 00:28:58,640
Brown's campaign has benefited greatly
from the support of President Kennedy, 

480
00:28:58,680 --> 00:29:00,560
while Nixon has had trouble
convincing voters

481
00:29:00,600 --> 00:29:02,920
this is not another run
for the presidency. 

482
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:06,000
With only a few precincts
left unreported, 

483
00:29:06,160 --> 00:29:07,920
all indications are of
another defeat for Nixon, 

484
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:12,080
who lost the presidency just two
years ago by a paper-thin margin. 

485
00:29:12,160 --> 00:29:14,400
It seems his brief political
comeback--

486
00:29:14,480 --> 00:29:18,120
You making a statement?

487
00:29:18,160 --> 00:29:20,040
Thank you, Fidel Castro. 

488
00:29:20,080 --> 00:29:23,080
You're not going to blame Castro.
-I sure am!

489
00:29:23,160 --> 00:29:26,000
Goddamn missile crisis united
the whole country behind Kennedy. 

490
00:29:26,040 --> 00:29:29,000
And he was supporting Brown.
People were scared, that's why. 

491
00:29:29,080 --> 00:29:31,040
I suppose Castro staged the
whole thing just to beat you. 

492
00:29:31,120 --> 00:29:33,800
Buddy, before you join the jubilation
of my being beaten again, remember:

493
00:29:33,840 --> 00:29:35,720
people vote not out of love
but fear. 

494
00:29:35,760 --> 00:29:39,200
They don't teach that at Sunday school
Or the Whittier Community Playhouse. 

495
00:29:39,280 --> 00:29:42,800
I'll go check with our people. 

496
00:29:42,880 --> 00:29:44,840
I'm glad they don't,
Dick, 

497
00:29:44,920 --> 00:29:48,880
because life is tough
and it is unfair, 

498
00:29:48,960 --> 00:29:51,800
and sometimes you forget that
in your self-pity. 

499
00:29:51,880 --> 00:29:54,920
Happy days are here again
-You forget sometimes, Dick, 

500
00:29:55,000 --> 00:29:57,920
that I had a life before you,
before California--

501
00:29:57,960 --> 00:30:00,240
Let us sing a song
Of cheer again--

502
00:30:00,320 --> 00:30:02,400
Cocksucker!

503
00:30:04,960 --> 00:30:08,560
Don't you want to listen to
Gov. Brown's victory speech?

504
00:30:08,640 --> 00:30:11,120
Nope. Not going to listen to
any more speeches ever again. 

505
00:30:11,200 --> 00:30:13,840
Amen to that. 

506
00:30:13,920 --> 00:30:17,480
It's over, Dick.
-I'll concede in the morning. 

507
00:30:17,560 --> 00:30:19,440
Not that. 

508
00:30:27,880 --> 00:30:29,760
Buddy?

509
00:30:48,040 --> 00:30:50,360
I have always
stood by you. 

510
00:30:50,440 --> 00:30:53,720
I campaigned for you
when I was pregnant. 

511
00:30:53,800 --> 00:30:57,560
During Checkers, when Ike
wanted you out, I told you to fight. 

512
00:30:59,120 --> 00:31:01,480
This is different,
Dick. 

513
00:31:01,520 --> 00:31:03,400
You've changed. 

514
00:31:04,880 --> 00:31:08,680
You've grown more bitter,
like you're at war with the world. 

515
00:31:08,720 --> 00:31:11,280
You weren't that way
before. 

516
00:31:13,760 --> 00:31:16,200
I'm 50 years old now,
Dick. 

517
00:31:16,280 --> 00:31:19,120
How many millions of miles
have I traveled?

518
00:31:19,160 --> 00:31:22,920
How many millions of peoples' hands
have I shaked that I just don't like?

519
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:25,320
How many thank-you notes
have I written?

520
00:31:25,400 --> 00:31:29,200
It's as if I, I don't know,
Just went to sleep a long time ago

521
00:31:29,240 --> 00:31:31,080
and missed
the years between. 

522
00:31:33,560 --> 00:31:35,960
I've had enough. 

523
00:31:37,640 --> 00:31:41,200
What are you saying?
What are you talking about?

524
00:31:42,560 --> 00:31:45,160
I want a divorce. 

525
00:31:45,240 --> 00:31:47,760
My God. Divorce?

526
00:31:48,880 --> 00:31:51,080
What about the girls?

527
00:31:52,120 --> 00:31:54,000
The girls'll grow up. 

528
00:31:54,040 --> 00:31:56,840
They only know you
from television anyway. 

529
00:31:56,920 --> 00:31:58,760
It'll ruin us,
Our family. 

530
00:31:58,840 --> 00:32:01,920
You're ruining us. If we stay with you,
you'll take us down with you. 

531
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:04,800
This isn't political, Dick.
This is our life. 

532
00:32:04,840 --> 00:32:07,680
Everything's political,
I'm political, you're political. 

533
00:32:07,760 --> 00:32:09,600
No, I'm not.
I'm finished. 

534
00:32:15,720 --> 00:32:18,520
Well, this is just
What they want, Buddy. 

535
00:32:19,560 --> 00:32:21,400
Don't you see?

536
00:32:24,320 --> 00:32:27,120
They want to drive us apart,
to beat us. 

537
00:32:28,280 --> 00:32:30,600
We can't let them
do it. 

538
00:32:30,680 --> 00:32:33,000
We've been through
too much together, Buddy. 

539
00:32:33,080 --> 00:32:35,440
We belong together. 

540
00:32:35,480 --> 00:32:38,840
That's what you said
the first time we met. 

541
00:32:38,920 --> 00:32:41,440
You didn't even know me. 

542
00:32:41,520 --> 00:32:43,360
Oh, yes, I did. 

543
00:32:46,360 --> 00:32:49,200
I asked you to marry me,
didn't I?

544
00:32:49,240 --> 00:32:51,120
On our first date. 

545
00:32:52,120 --> 00:32:53,960
I said it
because I knew--

546
00:32:55,280 --> 00:32:57,640
I knew
you were the one. 

547
00:32:59,360 --> 00:33:01,440
So solid. 

548
00:33:01,480 --> 00:33:04,080
So strong. 

549
00:33:04,160 --> 00:33:06,240
So beautiful.
-I'm Pat Ryan. 

550
00:33:06,320 --> 00:33:08,160
Uh, 

551
00:33:08,240 --> 00:33:10,760
Richard Nixon.
-Pleasure to meet you. 

552
00:33:10,840 --> 00:33:13,560
Pleasure to meet you. 

553
00:33:25,640 --> 00:33:29,920
Are you happy I called?
-In a way, yes. 

554
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:32,080
Don't tell me you've been
cutting my part. 

555
00:33:32,160 --> 00:33:35,440
Of course, honey, you know I would
never deceive you. Don't you?

556
00:34:03,360 --> 00:34:06,640
You were the most beautiful
thing I'd ever seen. 

557
00:34:08,640 --> 00:34:11,040
I don't want to lose you. 

558
00:34:13,240 --> 00:34:15,080
Ever. 

559
00:34:15,160 --> 00:34:17,040
Dick, don't. 

560
00:34:23,080 --> 00:34:25,880
You really want me
to quit?

561
00:34:29,320 --> 00:34:31,160
We can be happy. 

562
00:34:32,720 --> 00:34:34,560
We really can. 

563
00:34:36,320 --> 00:34:39,120
The girls and I
love you, Dick. 

564
00:34:42,640 --> 00:34:44,480
And if I stop

565
00:34:44,520 --> 00:34:48,000
there'll be
no more talk of divorce?

566
00:34:57,240 --> 00:34:59,080
I'll do it. 

567
00:34:59,160 --> 00:35:01,560
No more. 

568
00:35:03,080 --> 00:35:05,240
Are you serious? 

569
00:35:05,320 --> 00:35:08,400
Yeah. I'm out. 

570
00:35:09,560 --> 00:35:12,120
Is that the truth?

571
00:35:14,240 --> 00:35:16,560
I'll never run again. 

572
00:35:16,600 --> 00:35:18,440
I promise. 

573
00:35:20,360 --> 00:35:22,240
Yeah. 

574
00:35:24,760 --> 00:35:27,080
I love you, Buddy. 

575
00:35:27,120 --> 00:35:28,920
I love you. 

576
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:30,840
I love you. 

577
00:35:33,840 --> 00:35:35,640
Where are they?

578
00:35:35,720 --> 00:35:38,520
Dick, you don't have to make a
statement. Herb covered 'em for you. 

579
00:35:38,600 --> 00:35:40,440
No!

580
00:35:40,520 --> 00:35:45,000
Gentlemen, Mr. Nixon
is a man who is graceful in defeat, 

581
00:35:45,080 --> 00:35:47,080
and if he was
here with us--

582
00:35:51,640 --> 00:35:53,680
Can I have
some quiet, please?

583
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:58,360
Give the--
just a second!

584
00:35:58,440 --> 00:36:02,280
Can I have some quiet,
please? Quiet!

585
00:36:02,360 --> 00:36:04,320
Thank you!

586
00:36:04,400 --> 00:36:06,840
Mr. Nixon!

587
00:36:06,920 --> 00:36:10,800
I believe Governor Brown has a heart, 

588
00:36:10,880 --> 00:36:13,680
even though he believes
I do not. 

589
00:36:13,760 --> 00:36:17,520
Uh, I believe
he's a good American, 

590
00:36:17,600 --> 00:36:20,240
even though he feels
I am not. 

591
00:36:20,320 --> 00:36:25,440
I'm proud of the fact that I defended
my opponent's patriotism. 

592
00:36:25,480 --> 00:36:29,080
Uh, you gentlemen didn't report it,
but I'm proud that I did that. 

593
00:36:31,360 --> 00:36:35,600
And I would appreciate it, for once,
if you would just print what I say. 

594
00:36:35,680 --> 00:36:37,760
Uh, for 16 years, 

595
00:36:37,800 --> 00:36:41,560
uh, ever since the Hiss case,
you've had a lot of fun. 

596
00:36:41,640 --> 00:36:43,480
A lot of fun. 

597
00:36:43,560 --> 00:36:46,320
But recognize you have
a responsibility, 

598
00:36:46,400 --> 00:36:50,160
if you're against the candidate,
to give him the shaft. 

599
00:36:50,240 --> 00:36:53,040
But if you do that, at least put one
lonely reporter on the campaign

600
00:36:53,120 --> 00:36:55,920
who will report
what the candidate says now and then. 

601
00:36:56,000 --> 00:36:59,600
Uh, I think, 

602
00:36:59,680 --> 00:37:02,800
all in all, I've given
as good as I've taken. 

603
00:37:02,880 --> 00:37:06,280
But as I leave you, I w--
I want you to know--

604
00:37:06,360 --> 00:37:09,360
Just think what you're
gonna be missing. 

605
00:37:09,440 --> 00:37:12,720
Uh, you won't have Nixon
to kick around anymore. 

606
00:37:12,800 --> 00:37:14,600
Kick around anymore. 

607
00:37:24,440 --> 00:37:27,120
Because, gentlemen,
this is my last press conference. 

608
00:37:27,200 --> 00:37:29,520
Thank you and good day.
-Mr. Nixon!

609
00:37:29,600 --> 00:37:32,280
Is this the end of politics for you?

610
00:37:40,520 --> 00:37:42,360
Here in California

611
00:37:42,440 --> 00:37:46,400
we can officially write the political
obituary of Richard Milhouse Nixon. 

612
00:37:46,440 --> 00:37:49,560
As mall town lawyer like Lincoln,
Nixon became a representative at 33

613
00:37:49,640 --> 00:37:51,560
and a senator at 35

614
00:37:51,600 --> 00:37:54,920
as part of the post war Republican sweep
of the congressional elections

615
00:37:55,000 --> 00:37:57,800
that attacked F. D. R. 's
big-government new deal. 

616
00:37:57,840 --> 00:38:00,320
Running as
a South Pacific veteran, 

617
00:38:00,400 --> 00:38:04,640
victories over Congressman Jerry Voorhis
and Senator Helen Gahagan Douglas

618
00:38:04,680 --> 00:38:07,080
made it clear that,
to Nixon, politics was war. 

619
00:38:07,160 --> 00:38:09,520
He didn't have opponents,
he had enemies. 

620
00:38:09,600 --> 00:38:12,400
Why, she's pink, right down
to her underwear!

621
00:38:12,480 --> 00:38:14,920
Nixon became one of
the leading lights

622
00:38:15,000 --> 00:38:16,960
on the notorious House Un-American
Activities Committee, 

623
00:38:17,040 --> 00:38:20,160
questioning labor leaders, Spanish Civil
War veterans, Hollywood celebrities. 

624
00:38:20,200 --> 00:38:22,880
If I had my way, they'd all
be sent back to Russia. 

625
00:38:22,960 --> 00:38:26,320
But it was the Alger Hiss case
that made Nixon a household name. 

626
00:38:26,400 --> 00:38:28,400
One of the architects
Of the United Nations, 

627
00:38:28,480 --> 00:38:30,760
intimate of F. D. R.
and Oliver Wendell Holmes, 

628
00:38:30,800 --> 00:38:33,480
Alger Hiss was
a State Department diplomat

629
00:38:33,520 --> 00:38:35,760
accused by freelance journalist
Whittaker Chambers

630
00:38:35,840 --> 00:38:37,680
of passing secret documents
to the Soviet Union. 

631
00:38:37,760 --> 00:38:41,800
Hiss is lying.
-Hiss claimed he was being set up

632
00:38:41,880 --> 00:38:44,920
by Nixon and J. Edgar Hoover to
discredit the new deal's policies. 

633
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:49,320
I am not, and never have been,
a member of the Communist party. 

634
00:38:49,400 --> 00:38:52,200
The case came down
to an Underwood typewriter

635
00:38:52,240 --> 00:38:55,240
and a roll of film
hidden in a pumpkin patch. 

636
00:38:55,280 --> 00:38:58,600
I asked Hiss if he'd known Chambers. 

637
00:38:58,640 --> 00:39:01,880
When he said no,
I knew he was lying; I knew I had him. 

638
00:39:01,960 --> 00:39:05,520
After two trials, Hiss was convicted
not of spying but of per jury. 

639
00:39:05,600 --> 00:39:08,480
To some, Nixon was a hero
and a patriot. 

640
00:39:08,560 --> 00:39:11,400
But to many, he was
a shameless self-promoter. 

641
00:39:11,440 --> 00:39:13,480
Eleanor Roosevelt
angrily condemned him. 

642
00:39:13,560 --> 00:39:17,480
Nixon continued to tear into Truman,
Acheson and the Democratic party

643
00:39:17,520 --> 00:39:20,240
for losing mainland China
in 1949

644
00:39:20,320 --> 00:39:22,920
and blamed the Korean War
on a weak foreign policy. 

645
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:25,960
I promise to expose and
to continue to expose

646
00:39:26,040 --> 00:39:28,360
the people that have sold
this country down the river!

647
00:39:28,400 --> 00:39:33,480
His speeches, if more subtle than those
Of his Republican all Joe McCarthy, 

648
00:39:33,560 --> 00:39:35,560
were just as aggressive. 

649
00:39:35,640 --> 00:39:40,240
The direct result of Truman's decision
is that China has gone Communist!

650
00:39:40,320 --> 00:39:43,080
Mao is a monster!
Why?

651
00:39:43,160 --> 00:39:46,400
Who in the State Department
is watching over American interests?

652
00:39:46,480 --> 00:39:48,800
Who has given the Russians
the atomic bomb?

653
00:39:48,880 --> 00:39:52,520
The Soviet Union is an example of a
slave state in the ultimate development. 

654
00:39:54,200 --> 00:39:57,280
Driven by demons that seemed
more personal than political, 

655
00:39:57,320 --> 00:40:02,080
Nixon became Eisenhower's
vice presidential candidate in 1952. 

656
00:40:02,160 --> 00:40:07,040
Then came the Checkers crisis. Nixon was
accused of hiding a secret slush fund. 

657
00:40:07,120 --> 00:40:10,400
About to be kicked off the ticket,
he went live on national television

658
00:40:10,440 --> 00:40:12,200
in an unprecedented
appearance. 

659
00:40:12,240 --> 00:40:16,040
I'm going to give to this television
audience a complete financial history. 

660
00:40:16,080 --> 00:40:18,920
Everything I've earned, spent,
-The list included their house, 

661
00:40:18,960 --> 00:40:21,800
their Oldsmobile, Pat's cloth coat.
-everything I own. 

662
00:40:21,840 --> 00:40:24,640
And lastly, in what was
to become history, 

663
00:40:24,720 --> 00:40:26,560
a sentimental gift
from a Texas businessman. 

664
00:40:26,600 --> 00:40:29,600
You know what it was?
It was a little cocker spaniel dog

665
00:40:29,640 --> 00:40:33,440
in a crate that he'd sent all the way
from Texas--black and white, spotted. 

666
00:40:33,520 --> 00:40:37,600
And our little girl Tricia,
the six-year-old, named it Checkers. 

667
00:40:37,640 --> 00:40:41,600
58 million people saw it.
-And like all kids, they love the dog. 

668
00:40:41,680 --> 00:40:44,960
It was shameless it was manipulative
-I just wanna say right now, 

669
00:40:45,040 --> 00:40:47,840
regardless of what they say about him,
we're gonna keep him. 

670
00:40:47,880 --> 00:40:49,880
It was a huge success. 

671
00:40:49,960 --> 00:40:52,800
He stayed on the national scene, 

672
00:40:52,840 --> 00:40:55,680
serving two terms as vice president
under Eisenhower. 

673
00:40:55,760 --> 00:40:58,080
Against Khrushchev
at the Kitchen Debate in Moscow

674
00:40:58,160 --> 00:41:00,240
and stoned by Latin mobs
in Venezuela, 

675
00:41:00,320 --> 00:41:03,720
Nixon once again became
a national hero. 

676
00:41:03,800 --> 00:41:06,760
But it all came to a crashing end
against Kennedy in 1960

677
00:41:06,840 --> 00:41:10,280
and Pat Brown
in California in '62. 

678
00:41:10,360 --> 00:41:13,400
And thus ends a great
American political story. 

679
00:41:13,480 --> 00:41:16,560
The truth is, we never knew who
Richard Nixon really was, 

680
00:41:16,640 --> 00:41:19,920
and now that he is gone
we never will. 

681
00:41:26,720 --> 00:41:31,520
Poor little Tricia.
-Her daddy couldn't get a job

682
00:41:31,600 --> 00:41:33,920
in this city
when he got out of Duke. 

683
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:36,800
Every white-shoe lawyer firm turned
me down. Didn't have the right look. 

684
00:41:36,840 --> 00:41:39,520
I couldn't even get into the F. B. I.
-Hi! How are ya?

685
00:41:39,600 --> 00:41:42,880
Did you catch that picture of you
in the news last week, Dick?

686
00:41:42,920 --> 00:41:45,760
You were standin' on Fifth Avenue.
-Oh, yeah. 

687
00:41:45,840 --> 00:41:47,680
You were lookin'
Straight ahead

688
00:41:47,760 --> 00:41:50,720
and everyone else was lookin' the other
way, like you just farted or somethin'. 

689
00:41:50,800 --> 00:41:53,480
It said-It said, 

690
00:41:53,560 --> 00:41:56,400
Who remembers
Dick Nixon?

691
00:41:56,440 --> 00:41:59,280
Unbelievable.
I was screamin'. 

692
00:41:59,320 --> 00:42:01,160
Yeah, that was hilarious,
Martha. 

693
00:42:01,240 --> 00:42:04,800
They were were waiting
For the light to change. 

694
00:42:04,880 --> 00:42:07,320
Typical of the press,
They wouldn't correct it--

695
00:42:07,400 --> 00:42:09,960
We oughta catch Rocky
before he leaves. 

696
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:12,640
I'm sure it's just
a run of bad luck, Mr. Nixon. 

697
00:42:12,680 --> 00:42:15,520
He can walk this direction, can't he?
-I don't know. 

698
00:42:15,600 --> 00:42:19,360
I've read some nice things about you.
-Maybe where you come from. 

699
00:42:19,440 --> 00:42:23,760
But where I come from, Dick Nixon is
as misunderstood as a fox in a henhouse. 

700
00:42:23,840 --> 00:42:25,680
And do you know why?

701
00:42:25,760 --> 00:42:29,160
Because, my darlin', they all think
that your smile and your face

702
00:42:29,240 --> 00:42:33,120
are never in the same place
at the same time. 

703
00:42:33,200 --> 00:42:36,040
You and me, we're gonna have to
work on that, sweetie. 

704
00:42:36,080 --> 00:42:38,280
Someone freshen Martha's drink.
She's down a quart. 

705
00:42:38,320 --> 00:42:40,200
Well, zip-a-dee-doo-dah!

706
00:42:40,240 --> 00:42:44,520
I think he is frightened by my charm.
-I know I am. 

707
00:42:44,600 --> 00:42:47,400
Pat can't stand her.
-It's a thing she does. 

708
00:42:47,480 --> 00:42:49,360
She talks at night. 

709
00:42:49,400 --> 00:42:53,160
Talks all day too. How the hell
can you put up with her, John?

710
00:42:53,240 --> 00:42:56,040
Well, I'm in love with her.
And she's great in bed. 

711
00:42:57,680 --> 00:43:01,000
If a Rockefeller can't become
president of the United States, 

712
